      <hedline>
        <hl1>Death-Penalty Qualms</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Stephen Adams letter, in response to Bob Herbert's Oct 9 Op-Ed article on emotional toll and ethical concerns of those who assist in death penalty process, says it is now time for lawyers to do the same</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bob Herbert reports that some of those who assist in the death penalty process are acknowledging the emotional toll it takes on them and the ethical concerns that it raises (column, Oct. 9). It is now time for lawyers to do the same.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bob Herbert reports that some of those who assist in the death penalty process are acknowledging the emotional toll it takes on them and the ethical concerns that it raises (column, Oct. 9). It is now time for lawyers to do the same.</p>
        <p>Capital punishment serves no purpose beyond revenge, to which the calling of lawyers and judges -- the pursuit of justice -- is entirely alien.</p>
        <p>Therefore, on every occasion that the state chooses to pursue the death penalty, it should be the collective  duty of all lawyers, including defendants' lawyers, and judges to decline to participate further. Without legal support, the machinery of death cannot go forward.</p>
        <p>STEPHEN ADAMS  Enterprise, Ore., Oct. 9, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a lawyer.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
